WEBVTT	#Elemental Media Engine(TM) 2.17.0.0

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.930


00:00:00.930 --> 00:00:02.820
Well, the IRS is facing a backlog

00:00:02.820 --> 00:00:07.290
of more than 23 million returns this tax filing season.

00:00:07.290 --> 00:00:09.720
Now, during a hearing before the Senate Finance Committee,

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:12.930
the agency said factors like budget cuts and retirements

00:00:12.930 --> 00:00:14.250
have led to understaffing.

00:00:14.250 --> 00:00:16.620
And that turns into poor customer service.

00:00:16.620 --> 00:00:19.680
The IRS has also taken on more responsibilities

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:22.320
during the pandemic to distribute economic relief.

00:00:22.320 --> 00:00:25.080
These problems could result in Americans

00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:28.650
seeing a delay in their refund checks this year.

00:00:28.650 --> 00:00:32.100
CBS News reporter, Sarah Ewall-wice,

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:33.540
joins me now with more.

00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:35.310
Sarah, so are we going to get delays

00:00:35.310 --> 00:00:37.500
on our tax return checks?

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:41.370
You know, it really depends on how you file your tax return.

00:00:41.370 --> 00:00:44.920
The IRS is begging people to file electronically

00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:47.820
and to double and triple check their information.

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:50.490
If they do that, they should be able to get their refunds

00:00:50.490 --> 00:00:52.710
in that 21-day window.

00:00:52.710 --> 00:00:55.560
But they really are facing unprecedented challenges

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:56.550
this tax season.

00:00:56.550 --> 00:00:59.160
And these really have been long-term issues

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:02.220
that the IRS is facing that has been exacerbated

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:04.080
by the coronavirus pandemic.

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:08.490
You talk about that backlog, 23 million items on its to-do list

00:01:08.490 --> 00:01:11.550
before it even addresses this tax filing season, which

00:01:11.550 --> 00:01:15.730
is making it a lot more work for a lot more people at the IRS.

00:01:15.730 --> 00:01:17.520
And what they're really saying is the heart

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:21.120
of that problem is those paper returns, which is why they want

00:01:21.120 --> 00:01:22.770
people to file electronically.

00:01:22.770 --> 00:01:25.410
Because the IRS has extremely old systems--

00:01:25.410 --> 00:01:28.290
they date back to the 1960s and 70s--

00:01:28.290 --> 00:01:30.300
and so when they have these paper returns,

00:01:30.300 --> 00:01:32.370
a lot of their systems are not automated.

00:01:32.370 --> 00:01:36.270
They have to go in and put information line-by-line

00:01:36.270 --> 00:01:37.860
into their systems.

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:42.060
After they were shut down in 2020 because of the pandemic,

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:45.510
for a number of months, they had to go back and work their way

00:01:45.510 --> 00:01:47.190
through all of that mail.

00:01:47.190 --> 00:01:49.840
That compiled up into last year.

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:52.650
So people were waiting for returns from 2020 last year,

00:01:52.650 --> 00:01:55.170
and some of them are still waiting for refunds this year

00:01:55.170 --> 00:01:56.790
on top of last year's returns.

00:01:56.790 --> 00:02:00.030
So a lot of challenges there, while they're seeing staffing

00:02:00.030 --> 00:02:02.560
shortages at the same time.

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:04.980
So it really is a challenge for them.

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:08.970
They're really pushing to have people file electronically--

00:02:08.970 --> 00:02:11.160
that is the top priority for them--

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:16.410
and to double and triple check those lines in their returns

00:02:16.410 --> 00:02:19.380
when people file, to make sure that they're all accurate.

00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:21.360
Yeah, because one mistake on one of those lines

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:22.920
could get your whole return rejected.

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:25.710
What kind of help is the IRS looking for right now

00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:27.900
to help alleviate some of these issues?

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:30.870
We saw them-- the Taxpayer Advocate

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:33.270
and some other officials-- at a hearing today.

00:02:33.270 --> 00:02:35.280
They talked about the challenges they're

00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:38.340
facing in terms of the IT systems

00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:39.840
at the IRS that are decades-old.

00:02:39.840 --> 00:02:43.380
And so they're asking for multi-year funding

00:02:43.380 --> 00:02:45.310
to help upgrade these systems.

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:47.100
This has been an ongoing issue that they've

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:49.860
been asking for funding for a while

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:53.760
now and asking to make all their systems modernized,

00:02:53.760 --> 00:02:54.600
bring them back--

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:57.420
bring them up into the 21st century, really.

00:02:57.420 --> 00:03:00.120
At the same time, they've been asking for more authorities

00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:01.500
in terms of hiring.

00:03:01.500 --> 00:03:04.080
We know that the IRS was looking to hire 5,000

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:06.450
people for tax-filing season.

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:11.370
They filled less than 200 of those open positions.

00:03:11.370 --> 00:03:14.880
And they're already facing reduced staffs at the IRS.

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:16.500
So that is another challenge.

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:19.450
They're asking to make that process easier.

00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:21.690
One thing I learned from this hearing today

00:03:21.690 --> 00:03:23.820
is to onboard some of these employees,

00:03:23.820 --> 00:03:26.490
it sometimes takes 60 to 120 days just

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:29.040
to onboard them before they can even begin training.

00:03:29.040 --> 00:03:31.500
So that's another challenge they're facing over there.

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:34.050
And the third thing they're really focusing on

00:03:34.050 --> 00:03:37.020
is customer service.

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:38.730
If people have questions-- more people,

00:03:38.730 --> 00:03:40.230
especially during the pandemic, have

00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:43.530
had questions-- they're calling the IRS at record levels.

00:03:43.530 --> 00:03:47.010
And they're only answering about 11% of phone calls.

00:03:47.010 --> 00:03:49.290
They're trying to get more of this information online,

00:03:49.290 --> 00:03:51.610
trying to make sure people can find it online.

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:54.600
So it's a continued process that they're working towards

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:56.910
because people are very frustrated and cannot get

00:03:56.910 --> 00:03:57.760
through.

00:03:57.760 --> 00:03:58.260
Yeah.

00:03:58.260 --> 00:03:59.640
I can imagine it'd be frustrating

00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:01.320
when you need help with a tax return

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:02.940
and you can't get an agent on the line.

00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:05.250
So file electronically-- that's one--

00:04:05.250 --> 00:04:07.180
and double check for errors.

00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:08.850
Now I want to switch gears a little bit.

00:04:08.850 --> 00:04:09.900
I want to talk about the economy.

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:11.370
I want to talk about inflation.

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:14.550
Democrats have floated this idea of suspending the gas

00:04:14.550 --> 00:04:16.420
tax to ease prices at the pump.

00:04:16.420 --> 00:04:18.060
You've spoken with a lot of experts.

00:04:18.060 --> 00:04:20.220
Do they think that would work?

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:22.920
Experts are not really sold on this idea

00:04:22.920 --> 00:04:26.490
when it comes to those who focus on tax policy and inflation.

00:04:26.490 --> 00:04:29.790
I spoke to folks from groups on the left and the right.

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:32.010
And they really said that while this could provide

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:34.530
some temporary relief, it's not really

00:04:34.530 --> 00:04:36.600
going to get at the heart of the issue.

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:39.060
Specifically, I spoke to someone at the Tax Policy Center

00:04:39.060 --> 00:04:42.570
who pointed out that the federal gas tax is just a little

00:04:42.570 --> 00:04:44.460
over $0.18 a gallon.

00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:46.470
If you waive that, for the average American,

00:04:46.470 --> 00:04:48.850
that'll save them about $2 a week.

00:04:48.850 --> 00:04:50.280
So when you go through this and go

00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:52.710
through the process of passing legislation to do something

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:56.100
like this, it really might not make much sense

00:04:56.100 --> 00:04:58.890
in the long run, specifically, because they might not

00:04:58.890 --> 00:05:01.640
see the huge difference anyway.

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:03.530
But on top of that, you have to factor

00:05:03.530 --> 00:05:06.050
in all the other components that are going on in the world

00:05:06.050 --> 00:05:08.600
right now that could impact energy prices.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:11.660
And even the things that are happening overseas-- the issues

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:14.430
with Ukraine-- could lead to a rise in energy prices.

00:05:14.430 --> 00:05:17.120
So even if they go through the process in Congress

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:21.620
and go through this, they might not have the relief from that

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:22.490
anyway.

00:05:22.490 --> 00:05:24.860
Something I will say, though, is that the White House has

00:05:24.860 --> 00:05:27.410
said they're open to this idea.

00:05:27.410 --> 00:05:30.340
Democratic leaders have also said they're open to this idea.

00:05:30.340 --> 00:05:32.420
But they haven't really come down in support of it

00:05:32.420 --> 00:05:32.960
specifically.

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:34.920
It's one of the things that they're looking at.

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:37.410
So I think it could be a challenge moving forward,

00:05:37.410 --> 00:05:39.770
especially in Congress, where even some Democrats

00:05:39.770 --> 00:05:43.130
and Republicans are not really in support of a gas tax

00:05:43.130 --> 00:05:44.390
holiday.

00:05:44.390 --> 00:05:45.890
It sounds like one way or the other,

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:48.170
we're probably going to be digging deeper at the gas

00:05:48.170 --> 00:05:49.650
pump in the coming weeks.

00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:53.080
Thank you very much for talking to us right now.